Remarks . No brooded eggs or embryos of this species were found, but largest female, 2 mm long from Dakar , had pereonites 2–6 swollen by about eight unspawned eggs. Another ovigerous female, 1.8 mm long, from Sheraton shore, Madeira, had about six eggs lling pereonites 3–5. The Dakar female still has her aesthetascs and pereopod wheel-joints, but the Sheraton one has lost them. Evidently this loss occurs before spawning the eggs, probably at an ecdysis associated with copulation. Moulting at mating is well-known in females of many Malacostraca (see e.g. Borowsky and Borowsky, 1987 ;
Karnovsky et al. , 1989
), including some isopods ( Nair, 1984 ).
